Leber hereditary optic neuropathy

  • maternally inherited bilateral subacute optic neuropathy
  • LHON typically produces severe and permanent visual loss
  • Predominantly affects males (85%)
  • onset : late teens.

[!TIP] Mnemonic: Affects, eyes, ears, brain, heart and movement -everything you need for sports ;)

Immune system

Components of the innate immune system:

  • Musocal barriers
  • Marcophages
  • Neutrophils
  • Complement system
  • Natural killer cells

Macrophage function

Macrophages function as

  1. Mediators of inflammation (see diagram below)
  2. Effectors of the immune response

Inflammatory role:

In addition to phagocytic and microbicidal actions, macrophages secrete cytokines which stimulate repair and sustain inflammation.

Effector role:
Macrophages function as effectors of adaptive immunity

  • Effectors of humoral immunity: Phagocytosing microbes coated with antibodies or complement
  • Effectors of cell mediated immunity: Macrophages are the most important phagocytes in the cell-mediated arm of adaptive immune responses. Macrophages respond to T helper cell signals which increase their killing ability, thereby functioning as effectors of cell mediated immunity.

Natural killer cells


NK cells are lymphocytes but do no express antigen specific receptors like T or B cells.
Balance between inhibitory and activating stimulation decides whether the NK cell kills the target cell or not.

  • MHC class I molecules are downregulated by a cell a in response to viral infections, other infections and stress.
  • Activator receptor binding molecules are expressed on cells with DNA damage, stress or infections.

NK cells can destroy cells without previous sensitization.

Killing is mediated by cytotoxic molecules which are stored within secretory lysosomes, a specialized exocytic organelle found in NK cells - Source

Important in destroying tumour cells.
Tumour cells may downregulated MHC-class I molecules to avoid detection by T cells. But loss of MHC-class I will activate NK cells. Therefore, NK cells and T cells function in a complementary fashion to eliminate tumour cells.

Antigen presenting cells

The main type of antigen presenting cell is the dendritic cell.
Other cells are also involved.
Dentric cell type 1: Dentritic cells

  • Present under epithelial surfaces and in interstitium to capture invading and circulating antigens, respectively.
  • Have high levels of MHC-Class II and T cell costimulatory molecules.
  • They capture and present antigens to T cells.

    Dendritic cell type 2: Follicular dentritic cells
  • Located in germinal centers of lymphoid follicles in the spleen and lymph nodes.
  • They have recetors for Fc porition of IgG and complement proteins.
  • Therefore, effectively bind opsonized antigens.
  • They display antigens to activated B cells for secondary antibody responses. They don't stimulate T cells.

Macrophages and B cells can also act as antigen presenting cells.

Ataxia telangiectasia

#autosomal-Recessive

There is a mutation in the ATM gene.

[!INFO] This gene is necessary for the action of tumour suppressors p53 and BRCA1.

One manifestation of the disease is increased susceptibility to malignancies.

  • Classic AT usually presents either at birth, with partial combined immunodeficiency, or in early childhood, when neurologic abnormalities begin.
  • Young children develop progressive cerebellar ataxia, abnormal eye movements, extrapyramidal motor dysfunction, and oculocutaneous telangiectasias.
  • Progressive pulmonary disease and hematologic malignancy are major causes of morbidity and mortality
  • Immunodeficiency (there is reduced number of T cells) is most commonly manifested by recurrent sinopulmonary infections.

CREST syndrome

The acronym "CREST" refers to the five main features: calcinosis, Raynaud's phenomenon, esophageal dysmotility, sclerodactyly, and telangiectasia.
Raynaud's phenomenon can precede the others by a long time. Source

- Beak like nose and microstomia
- telangiectasiaa and dilated nail fold capillary loops.

Diagnosis

  • ANA is positive in 95%.
  • Anti-centromere (ACA) -> associated with limited cutaneous type.
  • [!TIP] C for centromere and cutaneous
  • Anti-topoisomerase -> Associated with Diffuse cutaneous type.

Caused by #autosomal-Recessive defect in ATP7B gene on Chromosome 13 which affects a copper transporting ATPase.
No male / female predominance.
